maml:description.maml:para: Creates a new output within a Stream Analytics job or updates an existing output. The name of the output can be specified in the .JSON file or on the command line. If both are specified, the name on command line will be used instead of the name in the file. If you specify an output that already exists and do not specify -Force parameter, the cmdlet will ask whether or not to replace the existing output. If you specify -Force parameter and specify an existing output name, the output will be replaced without confirmation.

The New-AzureStreamAnalyticsOutput cmdlet creates a new output within a Stream Analytics job or updates an existing output. The name of the output can be specified in the .JSON file or on the command line. If both are specified, the name on command line will be used instead of the name in the file. If you specify an output that already exists and do not specify -Force parameter, the cmdlet will ask whether or not to replace the existing output. If you specify -Force parameter and specify an existing output name, the output will be replaced without confirmation.

dev:remarks.maml:para: Description
This command creates a new output called "output" in the job StreamingJob. If an existing output with this name is already defined, the cmdlet will ask whether or not to replace it.
Description
This command replaces the definition for "output" in the job StreamingJob.

maml:description.maml:para: Creates a new Stream Analytics job in Microsoft Azure or updates the definition of an existing specified job. If you specify -Force parameter and specify an existing job name, the job definition will be replaced without confirmation.

If you specify a job name that already exists and do not specify -Force parameter, the cmdlet will ask whether or not to replace the existing job. If you specify -Force parameter and specify an existing job name, the job definition will be replaced without confirmation.

maml:description.maml:para: Asynchronously stops a Stream Analytics job from running in Microsoft Azure and de-allocates resources that were that were being used. The job definition and meta-data will remain available within your subscription through both the Azure Portal and Management APIs, such that the job can be edited and restarted. You will not be charged for a job in the Stopped state.

The Stop-AzureStreamAnalyticsJob cmdlet asynchronously stops a Stream Analytics job from running in Microsoft Azure and de-allocates resources that were that were being used. You will not be charged for a job in the Stopped state.
